Univariate Linear Regression on the California Housing Prices Dataset¶

1. Framing the Problem:¶

The goal of this report is to conduct univariate linear regression on the California Housing Prices Dataset. Specifically, we aim to build three separate models to predict median house value based on each of the following independent variables: median income, population, and number of households.

2. Getting the Data¶

Here's the link to data source

print("Median House Value Range:", median_house_value_range, "\n")

Observations:

Median House Value is capped at 500001. So to accurate analysis we must trim all enties of 500001.

Data for Population and number of Households has a very wide range.

In [ ]:
housing_preprocessed = housing[housing.median_house_value != 500001]

4. Linear regressions¶

In [ ]:
model1 = LinearRegression()
model1.fit(X=housing_preprocessed[["median_income"]], y=housing_preprocessed[["median_house_value"]])

model2 = LinearRegression()
model2.fit(X=housing_preprocessed[["population"]], y=housing_preprocessed[["median_house_value"]])

model3 = LinearRegression()
model3.fit(X=housing_preprocessed[["households"]], y=housing_preprocessed[["median_house_value"]])

5. Summary¶

In [ ]:
# Calculate mean squared error and mean absolute error for each model
mse1 = mean_squared_error(housing_preprocessed[['median_house_value']], model1.predict(housing_preprocessed[['median_income']]))
mae1 = mean_absolute_error(housing_preprocessed[['median_house_value']], model1.predict(housing_preprocessed[['median_income']]))
r_squared1 = model1.score(housing_preprocessed[['median_income']], housing_preprocessed[['median_house_value']])

mse2 = mean_squared_error(housing_preprocessed[['median_house_value']], model2.predict(housing_preprocessed[['population']]))
mae2 = mean_absolute_error(housing_preprocessed[['median_house_value']], model2.predict(housing_preprocessed[['population']]))
r_squared2 = model2.score(housing_preprocessed[['population']], housing_preprocessed[['median_house_value']])

mse3 = mean_squared_error(housing_preprocessed[['median_house_value']], model3.predict(housing_preprocessed[['households']]))
mae3 = mean_absolute_error(housing_preprocessed[['median_house_value']], model3.predict(housing_preprocessed[['households']]))
r_squared3 = model3.score(housing_preprocessed[['households']], housing_preprocessed[['median_house_value']])

# Create a DataFrame to store the results
data = {
    'Model': ['House-Value vs Income', 'House-Value vs Population', 'House-Value vs Households'],
    'Intercept': [model1.intercept_[0], model2.intercept_[0], model3.intercept_[0]],
    'Slope': [model1.coef_[0][0], model2.coef_[0][0], model3.coef_[0][0]],
    'R-squared': [r_squared1, r_squared2, r_squared3],
    'Mean Squared Error': [mse1, mse2, mse3],
    'Mean Absolute Error': [mae1, mae2, mae3]
}

# Define the headers for the table
headers = ['Model of Median values', 'Intercept', 'Slope', 'R-squared', 'Mean Squared Error', 'Mean Absolute Error']

# Define the format for floating-point numbers
floatfmt = (".5f", ".5f", ".5f", ".5f", ".5f")

# Print the table using tabulate with the specified float format
print(tabulate(data, headers=headers, tablefmt="fancy_grid", floatfmt=floatfmt))

7. Conclusion¶

After visual inspection of plots and calculating the 'coefficient of determination' (R-squared), it is evident that Model-1 i.e. Medain House Value v. Median Income has the best fit among all three models.

From the Coeffient analysis, it seems the Median House Value is strongly affected to Median Income but is least affected by population.
